<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-11-30T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-11-30T19:00:00-05:00" n="529" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d529">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51W89 France/1058: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-11-30T19:00:00-05:00">November 30, 1936—7
                                        p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>487, Your 1160, November 28, 1 p.m. I entirely approve of your
                                restrained response to matters brought up in your interview as
                                reported in the telegram referred to above and in my opinion these
                                matters should be allowed to remain in abeyance until the President
                                has returned to Washington.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Moore</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>